Delicious food & reasonable prices - can't ask for much more! Ordered delivery of the spicy falafel pita and the eggplant a la Yafa pita. Both were delicious. Got some of the best dolmas around on the side - lemony, garlicky, and full of flavor. Hummus was rich & heavy on the tahini (as it should be!), and the pitas were full of fresh, flavorful veggie salads to balance the eggplant/falafel and sauces. This is going to become a take-out go to for us, I can already tell, and looking forward to visiting in a post-pandemic world.

Updated: stay away, long hair in food! The ppl that work there mostly have long/shaggy hair and no one wears a hair net. I ordered some food through an app (grape leaves and falafel pita) to find a long reddish hair packaged with my grape leaves. DO NOT GO HERE! NOT A CLEAN ENVIRONMENT. How hair is in a clear package with individually wrapped grape leaves does not make sense to me. I cook with my Afro out and hair doesn’t make it in my food. They need everyone to wear hair nets, especially if they are shedding.  The food here is decent when done right. This is the fourth, maybe fifth time that I’ve ordered well-done/crispy seasoned fries with my order and they’re damn near raw. Like, not even cooked all the way through. The thing about this place is when you order take-out they fold and staple the bag which is ultimately what deterred me from checking to see if the order was right. The customer service is mediocre whenever there’s a male cashing. The red-haired woman is the best customer service I’ve ever received and I’ve been coming here for at least a year; she will always give you grade a customer service. While I’m leaving a review, their pita portions are extremely inconsistent. Before, I noticed they were only full when I didn’t order with a coupon. Now they are mostly skimpy and decent once in a while. Please check your order when getting take-out! They use that as an excuse to mess up. I will post a pic of a fry broken in half to show how not crispy and not seasoned this is. It’s a shame that ppl who spend money (that work there) can’t appreciate or respect the fact that someone’s money is being spent to get a specific and quality product. Again, I’m only writing this review because it seems to happen all the time. Kulushkat needs to get their restaurant together. I will try to put a review every time my order is messed up and I don’t get a chance to check it. Hopefully they will do better because I do enjoy the food here (when made properl

The people are friendly and the restaurant has a crunchy organic vibe.  There are no tables -- just stools next to a bar that runs around the perimeter of this small store.  When we walked in we were greeted warmly.  They were playing bachata, which I thought was a little strange, but I like bachata, so that was cool.  The falafel sandwiches are good, but there were a few things that prevented me from fully enjoying them, and falafel is one of my most favorite foods.  First, I love purple cabbage, but there was simply too much of it.  The purple cabbage overpowered the sandwich, ruining the delicate flavors of tahini and falafel.  Secondly, the purple cabbage was cooked with caraway seeds.  I hate caraway seeds.  Why do they do that?  I've never heard of caraway seeds on a falafel sandwich before!  The falafels themselves were delectable and the tahini was wonderful.  I've had falafel sandwiches that I've liked better, but these were OK, hence, the 3 star rating "A-OK".
